arXiv.abstract:
Tau-lepton decays with up to two $\pi^0$'s in the final state, $	au^+ 	o \pi^+  ar{
u}_	au$, $ho^+ (\pi^+\pi^0)  ar{
u}_	au$, $a^+_1 (\pi^+\pi^0\pi^0)  ar{
u}_	au$, are used to study the performance of the barrel part of the silicon-tungsten electromagnetic calorimeter (Si-W ECAL) of the International Large Detector (ILD) at the future $e^+-e^-$ International Linear Collider. A correct reconstruction of the tau decay mode is crucial for constraining the tau spin state and measuring the Higgs boson CP state in $H	o 	au^+	au^-$ decays. About 95% of $\pi^+  ar{
u}_	au$ and 90% of $ho^+ ar{
u}_	au$ and $a^+_1 ar{
u}_	au$ decays from $e^+e^-	o Z^0	o 	au^+	au^-$ reaction at $e^\pm$-beam energy of 125 GeV are correctly reconstructed. In a smaller ILD detector, with Si-W ECAL radius reduced by about 20% these numbers degrade by at most 2%. The $\pi^0$ mass resolution stays below 10%. Since the failures in the tau-lepton reconstruction are mainly due to photons, the increase of the ILD magnetic field from 3.5 T to 4 T does not bring any significant improvement.

